      {
        "id": "mineru_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We use similar language to that on page 210, with appropriate modifi cations:",
        "bbox": [
          0.11764705882352941,
          0.7830303030303031,
          0.7254901960784313,
          0.8018181818181818
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The SLR(l) parsing algorithm. Let s be the current state whose number is at the top of the parsing stack. Then actions are defined as follows:",
        "bbox": [
          0.11294117647058824,
          0.8187878787878788,
          0.836078431372549,
          0.8527272727272728
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_jiaocaineedrop_chap5.pdf_4_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "(1) If state s contains any item of the form A → α.X β, where X is a terminal, and X is the next token in the input string, then the action is to remove the current input token and push onto the stack the number of the state containing the item A → αX. β.",
        "bbox": [
          0.11529411764705882,
          0.8551515151515151,
          0.883921568627451,
          0.9096969696969697
        ],
        "order": 8
